               <msContents>
                  <summary> This <title>Farasnāmah</title> (Book of Horses) more often appears under
                     a variant title <title>Risālah dar Ṣaydīyah</title> by <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied"
                        key="person_50013027" role="att" change="#role-assignment">Shaykh ʿAlī Ḥazīn
                        (d. ca. 1767)</persName>. The work contains an introduction on the
                     legality of hunting, followed by the first chapter that presents various land
                     and sea animals by name, a second on their origins, and a third on their senses
                     and faculties. A scribe named <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Faz̤l Allāh
                     </persName> possibly copied this manuscript in the <placeName cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</placeName> during the <date cert="medium"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1800">18th century
                        CE</date>.</summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_731-item1">
                     <author key="person_f5826" change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied"
                           key="person_50013027" role="att" change="#role-assignment">Ḥazīn
                           , ʿAlī, d. ca. 1767)</persName>; <lb/> <persName xml:lang="ar">شيخ علي حزين
                           </persName> 
                     </author>
                     <editor role="scr" key="person_f8642">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"> Faz̤l Allāh </persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName>فضل الله</persName>
                     </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_11074">Risālah dar Ṣaydīyah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_11074">رساله در صید</title>
                     <title type="alt" xml:lang="fa" key="work_11074">Taẕkīra-'i Ṣaydīyah</title>
                     <title type="alt" xml:lang="fa" key="work_11074">رسالهٔ صیدیه</title>
                     <title type="alt" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_11074">Risāla dar Khavāṣṣ-i
                        Ḥayvānāt</title>
                     <title type="alt" xml:lang="fa" key="work_11074">رساله در خواض حیوانات</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmala"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> سواران مضمار بندگی و سرافکندگی را چه مجال </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="23b" to="23b"> برگ ۲۳پ (folio 23b):</locus> ...و چهار روز بعد
                        از آن هم شیر را بدهر دوزد همان پی بس است در خصول مقصود بی نظیر است. </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa"> اکنون بضبق اختتام این رساله <damage>نماید</damage>
                        ربنا اختم عواقباط(؟) تمام شد </colophon>
                     <colophon><locus from="1a" to="1a"> برگ ۱ر (folio 1a):</locus> تمت تمام شد، تمت
                        هذه الرسالة یوم السبت بید الفقیر الحقیر فضل الله فی شهر شعبان </colophon>
                     <colophon>Two colophons, the end of the text uninformative; however, the
                        conclusion copied on the folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears the
                        signature of <persName>Faz̤l Allāh</persName> and a partial date of <q
                           xml:lang="en">...Saturday... in the month of Sha‘bān</q>, with the say
                        and year ommitted.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>Note that in his handlist, Michael Kerney misidentified this manuscript
                        as <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7234"><idno>Persian
                              MS 732</idno></ref>. For another text on this topic attributed to the
                        same author, see see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7112"><idno>Persian
                              MS 610</idno></ref>.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of straight-grained, unevenly formeds and heavily
                           flocked, externally lightly sized and polished, buff-coloured
                              <material>paper</material> probably handmade in the <placeName
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> with ~7 laid lines
                           per cm and no discernible chain lines.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folio" quantity="23">23 folios, 2 flyleaves (ff. i + 23 +
                              i)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>270</height>
                              <width>184</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>228</height>
                              <width>135</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Modern pencilled Arabic numerals added to the
                           upper-left corners of the a sides.</foliation>

                        <collation> Two quaternions and a ternion 2IV+1(17)1III(23).
                              <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of the lower-left corners of
                              the b sides.</catchwords></collation>


                        <condition>Hand text with caution. In fair but stable condition, with water
                           and insect damage and historical repairs throughout.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>


                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="19" n="mistara"> Written in 1 column with 19
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in a hasty
                           <material>black</material> nasta‘līq hand with shikastah ligatures.
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>

                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label> The <locus from="ia" to="ia">right flyleaf a side
                        (f. ia)</locus> bears the title of the work and the name of former owner
                        <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                        change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton </persName>,
                     possibly in the hand of his assistant <persName key="person_f6587" role="wst"
                        >Muhīn Dās</persName>.<lb/>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">1/E</q>, and <q
                        xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">648</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed out
                     and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">731</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1862" notAfter="1867">
                        <p>Probably bound in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535"
                              >Delhi</placeName> for former owner <persName type="supplied"
                              key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                              William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> between <date
                              calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1861" notAfter="1868">1862 to
                              1867</date></p>
                        <p>Sewn on two stations, unsupported. Endpapers of comparatively rough
                           cross-grained paper added to the beginning and end. Edges trimmed and the
                              <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> edge spattered. Covered in
                           half reddish-brown goatskin <material>leather</material>, hollow-backed,
                           with defined joints and squares along the edges (Type III binding per
                           Déroche), with the <locus from="Upper_cover" to="Upper_cover">right
                              board</locus> faced with a predominantly brown 'Spanish" waved marbled
                           pattern with blue veins, while the <locus from="Lower_cover"
                              to="Lower_cover">left board</locus> bears a predominantly dark blue
                           'Stormont' patterned marbled paper sides with green and brown veins.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"><locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus> bears
                           an octagonal paper label with the title in nasta‘līq script.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>280</height>
                              <width>191</width>
                              <depth>10</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In sound but fair condition, with
                           extensive external abrasion and opening to the gutter margins restricted.
                        </condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Completed by <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Faz̤l Allāh </persName>,
                     probably in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace> undated, possibly <date cert="medium"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1800">18th century
                        CE</date>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied"
                           key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                           William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> who served in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                           >India</placeName>
                        <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>,
                        latterly as Commissioner in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535" key="place_7001535"
                           >Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian
                        manuscripts, from which the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252"
                           >British Museum</orgName> purchased 352 from his widow, <persName
                           key="person_f8470" role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton
                           (1817–1893)</persName>, now held in the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>
                        <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058"> Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder of Hamilton's collection
                     in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date> for <orgName
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
